stylometry: One type of probability distribution is a normal distribution.  Normal probability distributions are typically bell-shaped.  For these distributions, it is nearly impossible to have a value that is 3 standard deviations from the mean.  One standard deviation from the mean represents roughly a 68% confidence level, while two standard deviations represent roughly a 95% confidence level.  Put another way, 95% of the values in the distribution will be within two standard deviations of the mean.  These distributions may not be appropriate in all situations.  If the data are skewed to one side or negative values are inappropriate, a different distribution may be more appropriate.
